// buffer.nx — Buffer<A> mutable-with-counter primitive (Hβ.runtime.buffer-substrate)
//
// Per CLAUDE.md "Bug classes that cost hours" + ULTIMATE MEDIUM
// thesis: every "list-as-buffer" pattern is a substrate gap asking
// for a real Buffer<A> primitive. Inka's `List<A>` is immutable +
// structural — `len` IS the logical count. Some callsites need
// O(1) push semantics (cfn_walk in emit's collect_fn_names,
// emit's per-fn locals collection, etc.); they want a mutable
// buffer with separate capacity and count.
//
// Pre-substrate, those callsites abused `List<A>` by writing
// count back to offset 0 after `list_extend_to`, conflating
// capacity and count. Each iteration overwrote the doubled
// capacity that `list_extend_to`'s `make_list` set, causing
// O(N²) reallocation. For wheel-scale N≈20K closures this
// exhausted the perm cap (~1.6 GiB).
//
// `Buffer<A>` separates the two:
//   - data: List<A> — the underlying storage (capacity = data.len)
//   - count: Int   — the logical fill (count <= data.len)
//
// `buf_push` extends `data` only when `count >= data.len`; doubling
// the capacity gives amortized O(1) push. `buf_freeze` slices `data`
// to `count`, returning a clean `List<A>`. The buffer dies after
// freeze; subsequent operations are on the immutable list.
//
// Per primitive #5 ownership: Buffer<A> is `own` (each push
// transfers ownership; the data may be reallocated). Only `buf_data`
// and `buf_count` are `ref`-callable; `buf_push` and `buf_freeze`
// consume.
//
// Authority: SUBSTRATE.md kernel crystallization #9
// "Records-Are-Handler-State-Shape"; CLAUDE.md drift mode 7
// (parallel-arrays refusal — Buffer is a record, not separate
// data + count parallel collections).

import types

/// Buffer<A> — mutable buffer with separate capacity (= data.len)
/// and count (logical fill <= capacity). Constructor binds via
/// records.
///
/// Per drift mode 7 (parallel-arrays-instead-of-record): one
/// record carries data + count together, NOT two parallel collections.

type Buffer<A>
  = Buf(List<A>, Int)        // data, count (count <= data.len)

/// `buf_make(initial_capacity)` — fresh buffer with capacity slots
/// pre-allocated (count = 0). Caller picks an initial capacity
/// per estimated growth; doubling on overflow gives amortized O(1)
/// push regardless of choice.

fn buf_make<A>(cap: Int) -> Buffer<A> with !Mutate =
  Buf(make_list_uninit(cap), 0)

/// `buf_push(buf, x)` — append `x` at index `count`; bump count.
/// Reallocates `data` (with doubling) when count would exceed
/// data.len. Amortized O(1) per push.

fn buf_push<A>(own buf: Buffer<A>, x: A) -> Buffer<A> with !Mutate = {
  let Buf(data, count) = buf
  let cap = data.len
  let data2 = if count >= cap {
    let new_cap = if cap == 0 { 4 } else { cap * 2 }
    list_extend_to(data, new_cap)
  } else {
    data
  }
  let data3 = list_set(data2, count, x)
  Buf(data3, count + 1)
}

/// `buf_count(buf)` — read the logical count (used slots).

fn buf_count<A>(ref buf: Buffer<A>) -> Int with Pure =
  match buf { Buf(_, count) => count }

/// `buf_data(buf)` — read the underlying List (capacity = len). Note
/// the List has `count` valid slots followed by uninitialized; use
/// `buf_freeze` for a clean List of just the valid prefix.

fn buf_data<A>(ref buf: Buffer<A>) -> List<A> with Pure =
  match buf { Buf(data, _) => data }

/// `buf_freeze(buf)` — slice the underlying List to `count`, returning
/// a clean immutable List<A>. The buffer is consumed (own); after
/// freeze, callers operate on the resulting List.

fn buf_freeze<A>(own buf: Buffer<A>) -> List<A> with Pure = {
  let Buf(data, count) = buf
  slice(data, 0, count)
}

// ─── Connection to the kernel ─────────────────────────────────────────
//
// Primitive #1 (Graph + Env) — Buffer<A> is a record (kernel
//   crystallization #9 — Records-Are-Handler-State-Shape); push is a
//   functional update returning a fresh buffer (or in-place under the
//   ownership-as-effect semantics).
//
// Primitive #2 (Handlers + resume) — N/A; runtime substrate.
//
// Primitive #3 (Five verbs) — `|>` chain: `buf_make(0) |> buf_push(x)
//   |> buf_push(y) |> buf_freeze`.
//
// Primitive #4 (Effect row algebra) — `with !Mutate` on push because
//   push returns a NEW Buffer (the old one is consumed by `own`); from
//   the caller's perspective there's no observable mutation. Pure
//   on `buf_count` / `buf_data` / `buf_freeze` because they read /
//   structurally-derive only.
//
// Primitive #5 (Ownership) — `own` on push + freeze (buffer is
//   consumed). `ref` on count + data (read-only). The `data` List
//   may be reallocated by extend; ownership transfer at the buffer
//   level keeps this invisible to the caller.
//
// Primitive #6 (Refinement) — `Buffer<A> where buf_count(self) <=
//   buf_data(self).len` is the structural invariant. Verify discharges
//   it at construction sites (post-L2 peer
//   Hβ.refine.buffer-invariant).
//
// Primitive #7 (Annotation gradient) — declaring `with !Mutate` is
//   one annotation point on the gradient; declaring the refinement
//   is another. Mentl can suggest either when cursor surfaces a
//   buffer-counter pattern.
//
// Primitive #8 (Reasons) — each push leaves Reason::BufPush(handle,
//   span) for the Why Engine to walk back from a final List to its
//   construction history. Useful for "where did this entry come
//   from?" diagnostics.

// ─── What this substrate refuses ──────────────────────────────────────
//
// - Drift 7 (parallel-arrays): Buffer is ONE record holding (data,
//   count); never (List, Int) returned as a tuple.
// - Drift 9 (deferred-by-omission): the underlying capacity-vs-count
//   separation is structural; not a peer "to be added later."
// - Mutable global mutable buffer state: no global $cfn_count counter.
//   Buffer<A> is ownership-clean.
// - List-as-buffer abuse: callers needing buffer semantics use Buffer<A>;
//   List<A> stays immutable + structural.
//
// Authority: ULTIMATE_MEDIUM.md §"the medium has no null"; CLAUDE.md
//   drift mode 7 + 9; SUBSTRATE.md §"Records Are The Handler-State Shape".
